{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512124"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:50:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.35,0.04,0.3,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4443"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94502"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7212"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46140"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner for a review of her hypertension. She has not been reviewed for about 12 months and is compliant with her medications. On review she reports fatigue and weight loss of 5kg in the past three months. She has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks about two or three glasses of wine at weekends. On examination her blood pressure is 136/80 mmHg, pulse 88/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Apart from the sign shown in the photograph (Image), the rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Budd-Chiari syndrome","Cirrhosis","Intrathoracic goitre","Renal cell carcinoma","Carcinoma of the stomach"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is obvious dilatation of the inferior and superior epigastric veins. These collateral channels have most likely developed as a result of obstruction to the inferior vena cava. In other words, these venous channels have developed to aid venous return to the heart. Of the listed options, compression by a renal tumour, such as a \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, is the most plausible diagnosis. It is not so much the tumour itself - which can extend along the renal vein, but formation of thrombus which can extend into and occlude the inferior vena cava.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProminent superficial venous channels may become evident in the \u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E. However, in these cases the collateral channels that have developed focus on backflow from the portal vein and - when visible - recanalisation and dilatation of the periumbilical veins with filling of the superficial epigastric veins as they radiate out from the umbilicus (the so-called caput medusae).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Budd-Chiari syndrome results from blockage of the hepatic veins and involves upper abdominal pain, hepatomegaly and/or ascites. Due to the ascites, there is often massive distension of the abdomen. This is obviously not the case in this patient. \u003Cstrong\u003ECirrhosis\u003C/strong\u003E is late stage fibrosis of the liver. Symptoms may be non-specific such as fatigue and weight loss and as the disease progresses late manifestations may include ascites, portal hypertension and hepatic encephalopathy, then leading onto decompensation and liver failure. If, and when portal hypertension is manifest by the development of a caput medusae, an abdomen swollen by ascites is usually apparent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst other malignancies can cause inferior and/or superior vena caval obstruction, these are usually tumours that have a direct impact on the cava or compression through metastatic (lymph node) spread. Enlarged para-aortic nodes could cause caval compression, but this would be very unusual for a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric carcinoma.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMediastinal masses may cause caval obstruction and certainly a large retrosternal \u003Cstrong\u003Egoitre\u003C/strong\u003E could cause obstruction of the superior vena cava - but the obstruction in this patient is at a lower point along the inferior vena cava.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Obstruction to the inferior vena cava can cause dilation of the epigastric veins as collateral circulation becomes established.","Venous migration and tumour thrombus formations occur in 4-10% of patients with renal tumours."],"references":["Nouh MA, Inui M, Kakehi Y. Renal Cell Carcinoma with IVC Thrombi; Current Concepts and Future Perspectives. Clin Med Oncol. 2008;2:247-56. doi: 10.4137/cmo.s464. Epub 2008 Mar 26. PMID: 21892286; PMCID: PMC3161638."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18976"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18976"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/912ba183-7700-4f97-ad19-985815344216.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/912ba183-770